      "SummaryText": "or all maintenance and plant personnel who operate or perform maintenance on the ammonia scrubber system.  Ammonia awareness training is also conducted for all employees who work in the building and immediate vicinity of the ammonia scrubber and components.  5.  All incidents that resulted in or could have resulted in a release to the environment are reported to the Environmental, Health & Safety Department for investigation.  The investigation team consists of the EHS Department, Smelter Management, and affected employees.  6.  Rules for contractors, maintenance activities and hot work permits exist.                                                                                                                                                                                       \n5 YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY\nOn July 13, 2004 A contract employee team was working on the ammonia system.  The scope of the work was upgrades to equipment.  The contractor was responsible for the purging of tank and lines so new valves and appurtances could be installed on the tank and a new solenoid valve, for remote shutoff, could be installed.  The contractor had partially purged the tank and lines on the first day of the project. On the second day of the project the contractor failed to open a valve on the process line to purge the line.  When the contractor attempted to unbolt a flange residual ammonia in the line released for an estimated 10-15 seconds. The contractor was in close proximity to the flange and experienced second degree burns of the face, left arm, chest.  Corrective action focused on the need for contractor to have a written checklist for working on equipment at customer locations \n\nEMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM\nEast Penn's Hazardous Materials Team is trained to the Operations Level.  Arrangements have also been made with the local (Berks County) Hazardous Materials Response Team to respond to leaks if conditions dictate or the release has the potential to have offsite consequ"
